If we go to our GitHub here, it's this API directory.

00:48.420 --> 00:51.240
You can see it's a little package.json.

00:51.240 --> 00:53.380
It's got fastify.

00:53.380 --> 00:55.720
And that's about it.

00:55.720 --> 00:57.780
It has a SQLite database.

00:57.780 --> 00:58.140
Okay.

00:58.140 --> 01:04.200
And I think it's just a – it's got all of our static assets in there as well.

01:04.200 --> 01:12.440
So it has the CSS, all of the pizza images, and all of the – yeah, like all that stuff

01:12.440 --> 01:15.900
I didn't want you to have to deal with.

01:15.900 --> 01:21.640
So – and then you can see here in the server.js, it's just a fastify project and doesn't

01:21.640 --> 01:25.780
really do any much more than this.

01:25.780 --> 01:27.780
But not stuff that you have to worry about at all.

01:28.140 --> 01:30.140
Okay.

01:30.140 --> 01:38.520
So, in whatever terminal that you're in, navigate to your API directory.

01:38.520 --> 01:44.580
So you can see I'm in completeintro.reactv9project slash API.

01:44.580 --> 01:55.140
Two things, npm install – again, vulnerabilities, no – doesn't matter, it's okay.

01:55.140 --> 01:57.280
And then npm – let's take a look at that.

01:57.280 --> 01:57.980
Okay.

01:57.980 --> 02:04.060
Let's do run dev, because that'll be just fine.

02:04.060 --> 02:05.060
Okay.

02:05.060 --> 02:12.740
And you should see something like this.

02:12.740 --> 02:17.140
So if you go to localhost 3000, it's going to give you some sort of 404 error or something

02:17.140 --> 02:20.480
like this.

02:20.480 --> 02:22.980
I think it's API slash pizzas.

02:22.980 --> 02:23.980
Yeah.

02:23.980 --> 02:24.980
If you go to API slash pizzas on port 3000, you should get – I think it's API slash

02:24.980 --> 02:25.980
pizzas.

02:25.980 --> 02:26.980
Yeah.

02:26.980 --> 02:32.360
If you go to API slash pizzas on port 3000, you should get 31 pizzas, I think is how many

02:32.360 --> 02:35.900
I had in there, or 32 actually.

02:35.900 --> 02:39.680
So what we want to do is we want to use Vite as the proxy.

02:39.680 --> 02:43.080
And again, you don't really need to understand this too in depth, but essentially we want

02:43.080 --> 02:48.580
to run our front end and our back end on the same port, right?

02:48.580 --> 02:52.740
So we want everything running through port 5173 so that we don't have to worry about

02:52.740 --> 02:53.740
cores.

02:53.740 --> 02:56.060
And if you don't know what that is, bless you.

02:56.060 --> 02:56.480
Okay.

02:56.980 --> 03:02.280
If you do know what it is, you've been where I am, right?

03:02.280 --> 03:03.900
So we're going to run everything through Vite.

03:03.900 --> 03:07.620
Luckily, Vite makes this very easy to accomplish.

03:07.620 --> 03:12.840
So I want you to open your Vite.config.js, and we're just going to add one little thing

03:12.840 --> 03:13.840
here.

03:13.840 --> 03:20.300
We're going to add server, and we're going to put a comma there, and we're going to add

03:20.300 --> 03:24.980
a proxy.

03:24.980 --> 03:26.900
And so you add basically things that you want to run.

03:26.900 --> 03:28.480
Because you want to be proxied through this.

03:28.480 --> 03:46.140
And so for slash API, you want to run that through target http://localhost 3000.

03:46.140 --> 03:51.000
If you have not stopped your server from earlier in the course, please do that now, or else

03:51.000 --> 03:54.780
this will interfere with this, by the way.

03:54.780 --> 03:56.760
And then you want to add a change origin.

03:56.760 --> 04:00.680
As well, there you go, 3000.

04:00.680 --> 04:06.880
Change origin to be true, and we're going to do that as well for public.

04:06.880 --> 04:17.880
Actually literally the exact same thing for public.

04:17.880 --> 04:18.880
That's it.

04:18.880 --> 04:23.660
So I added this.

04:23.660 --> 04:26.240
This is going to proxy all of the requests from...

04:26.760 --> 04:36.760
Localhost colon 5173 on API and public to localhost 3000.

04:36.760 --> 04:43.520
So just to kind of prove my point here, I'm running my Vite server here.

04:43.520 --> 04:49.980
I'm going to open this in my localhost, and if I do slash API slash pizzas like we were

04:49.980 --> 04:54.420
just looking at, notice it still goes to that same API.

04:54.420 --> 04:55.680
So notice that this and this, despite the fact that they're on the same server, they're still

04:55.680 --> 04:56.680
on the same server.

04:56.680 --> 04:58.560
They're on different ports.

04:58.560 --> 05:03.180
Same thing, right?

05:03.180 --> 05:04.820
That's all that that does for you.

05:04.820 --> 05:06.360
It makes local dev much easier.

05:06.360 --> 05:11.580
You used to have to do some black magic and some seances to get this to work correctly.

05:11.580 --> 05:13.360
Now Vite makes it very easy.

05:13.360 --> 05:14.360
Yeah?

05:14.360 --> 05:18.520
Would that work for any localhost number then?

05:18.520 --> 05:21.680
It's just specifically looking for anything following API.

05:21.680 --> 05:22.680
Yep.

05:22.680 --> 05:25.680
So it's only processing things after the API, and it doesn't even have to be localhost,

05:25.680 --> 05:26.680
right?

05:26.680 --> 05:30.800
You can proxy it to your database in the cloud, right?

05:30.800 --> 05:32.340
Because you're just saying what the target is.

05:32.340 --> 05:34.200
The target can be anything, right?

05:34.200 --> 05:40.080
We're just doing it now in localhost, but this could be your lambdas on AWS or something

05:40.080 --> 05:41.080
like that.

05:41.080 --> 05:44.760
It's a pretty cool feature.

05:44.760 --> 05:45.760
I think it is.

05:45.760 --> 05:48.020
Even if this doesn't make total sense, as long as this is working, you don't have to

05:48.020 --> 05:50.880
think about it anymore, which is probably half the benefit as well.

